Bases on the historical voting of the the state

A recent article by The Economist has again reminded me of the very real possibility that Jim Hood might win the popular vote but still lose the election. Mississippi's constitution has Jim Crow-era provision that "statewide officers must win a majority of the popular vote and a majority of the 122 districts comprising the state’s House of Representatives. If no one wins a double-majority, the House may choose the governor." [1] I have thus assigned most of the ~15% chance that I give to a Hood popular vote victory to the "none of the above" option in which Hood wins the popular vote but Reeves is selected by the Republican majority in the House. I have increased this probability because, according to The Economist article, Tate Reeves has "refused to rule out letting the House decide." See my earlier post for more of my reasoning on this: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/901186

Reeves is now leading in the polls by just a few percentage points. Moreover, Reeves also had $1 million more (translated to about 80 percent more) to spend in the final weeks and Trump remains popular and impeachment unpopular. Trump will also appear just prior to the election. There are virtually no undecideds so the race will turn on turn out. I did not find any information about voter enthusiasm by party relating to Mississippi or nationally after yesterday's impeachment vote. Democrats still lead nationally. Yet, interestingly, there was a slight uptick among Republican voters in favor of an impeachment inquiry. Balancing the different factors, I think Reeves will win.

Current polls and an election system requireing majority vote and majority of House districts, before giving the vote to the House (currently controlled by the GOP). From: https://www.wjtv.com/news/local-news/us-judge-not-blocking-multistep-mississippi-election-system/ "Mississippi’s 1890 constitution requires a statewide candidate to win a majority of the popular vote and a majority of the 122 state House districts. If nobody wins both, the election is decided by the House, and representatives are not obligated to vote as their districts did."

Mississippi voters will decide the only open-seat gubernatorial race of 2019 as Gov. Phil Bryant (R) is prevented by term limits from seeking re-election. State Attorney General Jim Hood (D), Lt. Gov. Tate Reeves (R), Bob Hickingbottom (Constitution), and David Singletary (I) are competing to succeed Bryant.

It would seem Mississippi tends to vote, in to power, candidates who have had relatively more positive limelight shed on themselves. Also, Lieutenant governors seem to have an advantage when they run for the governor's office. Furthermore, the demographics of the state favors republicans.

Slightly increasing the bins in which Tate Reeves wins the election in light of President Trump's recent endorsement of Reeves on Twitter - in the past, such public endorsements by Trump have provided Republican candidates with a "Trump bump."

The Republicans look strong in this state. Based on historical results I'd say the Republicans are about 70-30 favourites. But Hood seems to be popular and has done alright in polls. For this reason I'd say the election will be tighter than history suggests. I'd still say its about 60-40 Republicans though. And I still think a convincing Republican win is most likely (5%+).

12% for none of the above because of the point that JC4841 made below.

Looking at Mississippi and how Republicans have done in Southern states, its safe to say that it will be a Republican victory statewide for the Governorship. However with that being said, Democrats will pick up some seats in the State legislature and the anti Trump Democrats will show up in mass to make the race close. Even with a large democratic turnout the population demographics and cultural mindset of Mississippi combined with the large number of registered Republicans it will still be Republican controlled at the end of the day.

In the past four gubernatorial elections, the Republican candidate has won by a margin of more than 5%.[1] The largest margin was in the most recent 2015 election, where the incumbent Republican governor (who is now term-limited and has endorsed Reeves) won by a 34-point margin.[2] President Trump won by an 18-point margin in 2016.[3] In 2018, Mississippi's incumbent Republican senator won re-election by a 19-point margin in a general election and Cindy Hyde-Smith won by a Senate special election by a 7-point margin despite notable missteps like joking about public hangings and suppressing the liberal vote.[4] Also, 2019 is not a presidential election year - in the past, Republicans have performed better in such years since overall turnout is lower. And finally, as others have pointed out, Mississippi is one of the most inelastic states in the country - meaning that we should take this base rate even more seriously.
@KitsonJ makes some good points about base rates favoring Reeves [1]. The latter is also somewhat ahead in most but not all polling [2].

Since 1992, the Republicans have won 6 of the 7 gubernatorial elections in Mississippi. Of those 6 republican victories, 5 have been over the margin of 5%. The one Democratic party victory, in 1999 was won by the dem candidate by 1.1%.
